14:
Great! That was your fastest time
today!
19:
I knew it! I'm finally starting to get
the hang of moving in the sand!
24:
You don't even know if your next
match will be a desert field, though,
right? And even if it is, how is a
bunch of sand entertaining to the
audience?
29:
Well, special fields come with their
own unique sets of challenges and
mishaps. That alone makes them
pretty popular.
32:
Although dealing with those
challenges IS hard on us athletes.
37:
I think you'll be able to handle it
though. You're pretty used to the
desert now.
41:
No way, I've got a looong ways to
go! I need to feel the desert right
down to my muscles, my very bones
themselves!
45:
The sand here really absorbs every
movement I make, which is perfect
for training! I need to do all I can toâ€”
63:
Ahaha, looks like a few of my
prosthetics overheated.
67: I-is that not cause for concern?
71:
I'm fine, I'm fine! A little cool-down
and a reboot is all they need.
75:
Hope I didn't scare you guys too
bad. Could you get me the water
from my bag?
82:
Ahhh, that's the stuff! I thought I'd
prepared for the desert heat, but I
guess not! Never underestimate the
real deal!
87:
You've only done virtual training
before this, right? Is it that different?
92:
Well, if you use high-end tech that
the stadiums use, you can get pretty
close to reality...
94:
But our team doesn't exactly have
the budget for that...
97:
Which is why I'm so thankful for you
all! I never dreamed I'd be able to
train like this!
102:
We're just happy to help. There's
only so much you can learn from a
replication, after all.
105:
Exactly! From the heat to the sand
itself, everything can be seen as a
threat.
109:
No matter how dustproof I make
myself, all it takes is a few grains of
sand to lock up my joints.
113:
Ah... I suppose that would be a huge
problem for machines.
118:
In that case, why not just throw sand
at your opponents? With any luck,
they'll break down and you'll
outnumber them.
123:
Th-that can't be considered fair
play, can it?
128:
And bombs and electric shocks are?
Come on now.
134:
Hmm... I suppose it wouldn't
TECHNICALLY be against the rules,
but I don't really want to play that
way.
137:
I totally see where you're coming
from though. Dirty tactics like that
are part of ActFast's appeal, and I'm
sure lots of fans would love to see it.
141:
But I want to compete using my own
abilities. I just want to enjoy ActFast
like any other sport.
145:
Haha, look at me being all
inspirational and junk. Sorry about
that. Hope I didn't come off too
corny.
149:
Not at all. Such thought processes
suit you, Middy.
158:
All right, I'm up and running, so let's
get started again! I wanna practice
dealing with an opponent, so
Nimbus, you're up!
167:
This is it, folks. The match you've all
been waiting for! Welcome to
Special Match: Desert Mode!
170:
Uhh... The other team's rackets look
an awful lot like shovels...
173:
They're definitely gonna use that
sand to play dirty.
177:
Well, regardless, there's nothing to
worry about. Middy's training in the
desert made sure of that. Besides...
180:
Anyone who prioritizes
handicapping their opponent over
actual strategy can't possibly beat
her.
183:
Thatâ€™s the signal! Let the match...
begin!
189:
An overwhelming victory, as
expected. Congratulations, Middy!
192:
Come on, I didn't do much. The
other team practically handed that
win to us.
197:
Haha, that was a riot! His leg got
caught in the sand, and when he
fell, he ended up eating it too!
201:
Well, I don't think that alone got you
the win. The way you were moving
out there was incredible!
205:
Hehe, thanks! I couldn't have done it
without the training you guys helped
me with.
209:
Our assistance mattered little. It was
your diligence that won the day.
213:
Well, in any case, I'm counting this
win as a team effort!
219:
Alright, this calls for a toast! Three
cheers to OUR victory!
